                    '4' => 'Thorough alarm assessment: analyses the alarm pattern critically — while the sequential detector activation matches the condensation pattern, three additional factors change the risk profile: (1) steward\'s independent report of electrical smell at a specific cabin location, (2) warm door indicating heat source behind it, (3) visible haze at door base distinct from overhead condensation. Recognises that these combined indicators are inconsistent with HVAC condensation and consistent with a cabin fire (possibly electrical — overloaded socket, charging device, cabin electrical fault). Treats as real fire. Immediately escalates to fire emergency procedures.',
                    '5' => 'Expert fire alarm analysis: rapid systematic differentiation — notes that the condensation false alarms showed detector activation without any corroborating physical signs (no smoke, no heat, no smell), whereas this alarm has three independent corroborating indicators (olfactory report, tactile heat on door, visual haze). Identifies that the 15-minute delay in the steward report means the fire has potentially been developing unreported, which makes the warm door particularly concerning — a cabin fire with 15+ minutes of development can be approaching flashover. Recognises the critical danger of "alarm fatigue" — the six previous false alarms have created a complacency bias that must be actively countered. Immediately declares fire emergency and escalates to the highest response level. Orders HVAC isolation for Zone 7 to prevent smoke spread, recognising that the HVAC system could be feeding oxygen to a developing fire and distributing smoke through the return air ducts.',
